Caption:
Thanks @harvard for referencing my ancestor Tangaku Fujita's 藤田丹岳 book, "Introduction to Sacred Studies" 聖學概論, in the Teikoku Toshokan. 

His pen name was Seitsu 世逸. Tangaku Fujita had two sons, Kensai Uda 宇田健斎 and Shosai Fujita 藤田升斎.
@bunkacho_japan

This book influenced many notable people. It can be even found in the personal library of Japanese Capitalism founder, and @jpx_official and @mizuhofg_official and @mizuho.inc founder, Eiichi Shibusawa. 渋沢栄一 

Tangaku was a doctor, Confucian scholar and teacher, prolific author, and an advisor to Governor Michitsura Honjo inside Fushimi Castle, Kyoto, Japan. @kyotonatmuseum

Michitsura Honjo was a descendant of Japanese Shogun, Tokugawa Tsunayoshi, who founded Yamagata city in Gifu. @furuta_hajime

More information on Tangaku Fujita and my ancestry can be read in historian Akira Haruta's book, "Sanyo Rai and Tangaku Fujita," at National Diet Library of Japan. @kokuritsukokkaitosyokan


